SIMPLE: stake
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stake
<hw>Stake</hw> <pr>(st⟦amac⟧k)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>staca</ets>, from the root of E. <ets>stick</ets>; akin to OFries.
& LG. <ets>stake</ets>, D. <ets>staak</ets>, Sw. <ets>stake</ets>, Dan.
<ets>stage</ets>. See <er>Stick</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>, and cf.
<er>Estacade</er>, <er>Stockade</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A piece of
wood, usually long and slender, pointed at one end so as to be easily
driven into the ground as a support or stay; <as>as, a <ex>stake</ex> to
support vines, fences, hedges, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A sharpened <qex>stake</qex> strong Dryas found.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A stick inserted upright in a loop, eye, or mortise,
at the side or end of a cart, a flat car, or the like, to prevent goods
from falling off.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The piece of timber to which a martyr was affixed to
be burned; hence, martyrdom by fire.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A small anvil usually furnished with a tang to enter
a hole in a bench top, -- used by tinsmiths, blacksmiths, etc., for
light work, punching upon, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>That which is laid down as a wager; that which is
staked or hazarded; a pledge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mormon Ch.)</fld> <def>A territorial division; --
called also <altname>stake of Zion</altname>.</def></p>

<p><q>Every city, or ⟦ldquo⟧<qex>stake</qex>,⟦rdquo⟧ including a chief
town and surrounding towns, has its president, with two counselors; and
this president has a high council of chosen men.</q>
<rj><qau>Schaff-Herzog Encyc.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>At stake</b></col>, <cd>in danger; hazarded;
pledged.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧I see my reputation is <xex>at stake</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Shak.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stake</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stake
<hw>Stake</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Staked</conjf> <pr>(st⟦amac⟧kd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Staking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To fasten, support,
or defend with stakes; <as>as, to <ex>stake</ex> vines or
plants</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To mark the limits of by stakes; -- with
<xex>out</xex>; <as>as, to <ex>stake</ex> out land; to <ex>stake</ex>
out a new road</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To put at hazard upon the issue of competition, or
upon a future contingency; to wager; to pledge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I'll <qex>stake</qex> yon lamb, that near the fountain plays.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To pierce or wound with a stake.</def>
<rj><au>Spectator.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stake-driver</ent>⟦br⟧
